AGI - US President Donald Trump has stated that he intends to speak with his Russian counterpart Vladimir Putin > tomorrow, Tuesday, March 18, to discuss how to end the war of Russia> in Ukraine. He told journalists on board Air Force One, specifying that he was already discussing to divide "certain goods" between the two countries.
<a href="https://www.agi.it/estero/news/2025-03-16/colloqui-trump-putin-Ukraine-30461284/">Trump</a> said that significant progress was made on the weekend and optimistic about a possible announcement after the chat. "I think we'll talk about land... We will talk about power stations," he said on board the plane, with the reporters present, confirming the interview with Putin to talk about the end of the war. "We have already discussed it a lot on both sides, Ukraine and Russia - it has added - we are already talking about it, the division of some goods". &nbsp;
The talks will address delicate issues such as the division of territories and the management of Ukrainian power plants, with the aim of achieving a ceasefire to start wider negotiations. The U.S. Special Envoy, Steve Witkoff, > reported that Putin showed openness to Trump's philosophy to end the conflict, although they remain reserves on key issues such as the control of Donetsk, Luhansk, Kherson and Zaporizhzhia regions. >
Europe continues its distrust of the relationship between Trump and Putin and the positions of the American president, very hard, towards Ukrainian President Volodymyr Zelenskyy, recalling how the Kiev leader was treated within the White House just over two weeks ago.&nbsp;

